	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				There are some interesting ideas presented here.  I'd just like to amplify one point.  The MacDonald's case is an interesting one, since at first blush it seems frivilous, but when you look at the details of the case it becomes a clasic example of what is right about this kind of litigation.  The real purpose of this kind of suit is to force change in business practices.<BR>
<BR>
The facts (as I remember them) are these.  MacDonald's coffee at the time was typically 180 degrees.  The industry standard for hot coffee is 160 degrees.  At 180 degrees it can melt the fat inside your body.  And this is what happened, it was a disfiguring injury.  They didn't describe the extent of the disfigurement, so I can't comment on that.  MacDonalds had refused to even pay the woman's medical expenses.  There had been several cases before which MacDonalds refused to settle.  The outcome was that MacDonald's changed their practices to lower the temperature of their coffee.  And given how big, rich and powerful MacDonald's is, its not clear to me that a smaller settlement than 3 Mil would have forced a change.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
